## `<file-level: imports>`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-1 -->

### Purpose
Tests that permission enforcement works end-to-end through the FUSE mount. The library layer's `perms.py` is the source of truth; this verifies that the adapter correctly forwards the kernel-supplied request context (uid/gid) and that EACCES propagates out to userspace.

These tests need the daemon running as a user whose identity can be observed; the fixture uses the current user's uid/gid.

### Implementation Notes

```python
import errno
import os
import pytest

pytestmark = pytest.mark.fuse
```

---

## `test_fuse_chmod_visible_via_stat(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-2 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary -->

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "f"
path.write_bytes(b"x")

os.chmod(path, 0o640)
assert os.stat(path).st_mode & 0o777 == 0o640
```

---

## `test_fuse_chmod_enforces_on_subsequent_open(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-3 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary; libc open() honors the kernel-level permission check -->

### Purpose
After chmod to 0o400 (owner read only), opening for write fails with EACCES. Daemon is running as the owner, so read still works.

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "f"
path.write_bytes(b"initial")
os.chmod(path, 0o400)

with pytest.raises(PermissionError) as e:
    open(path, "wb")
assert e.value.errno == errno.EACCES

# Read still works.
with open(path, "rb") as f:
    assert f.read() == b"initial"
```

---

## `test_fuse_chown_requires_privilege(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-4 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary + kernel privilege checks -->

### Purpose
chown to another user requires CAP_CHOWN (root). Non-root daemon reports EPERM.

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "f"
path.write_bytes(b"x")

# Attempt to chown to uid 0 when running as non-root.
if os.geteuid() != 0:
    with pytest.raises(PermissionError) as e:
        os.chown(path, 0, 0)
    assert e.value.errno == errno.EPERM
```

---

## `test_fuse_mode_bits_denied(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-5 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary -->

### Purpose
Creating a file with mode 0o000 and then trying to read it from the same process — EACCES (owner bits deny all).

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "locked"
# umask may strip bits; set mode explicitly after create.
path.touch()
os.chmod(path, 0o000)

with pytest.raises(PermissionError) as e:
    open(path, "rb")
assert e.value.errno == errno.EACCES
```

---

## `test_fuse_directory_execute_bit_required_to_traverse(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-6 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary -->

### Purpose
Reaching a file inside a directory with no execute bit fails with EACCES on the directory, not on the file itself.

### Postconditions

```python
(mount / "d").mkdir()
(mount / "d" / "f").write_bytes(b"content")

os.chmod(mount / "d", 0o600)   # read but no execute on dir
with pytest.raises(PermissionError) as e:
    open(mount / "d" / "f", "rb")
assert e.value.errno == errno.EACCES
```

---

## `test_fuse_utimes(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-fperm-7 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: syscall boundary -->

### Postconditions

```python
path = mount / "f"
path.touch()

os.utime(path, ns=(1_000_000_000_000, 2_000_000_000_000))
st = os.stat(path)
assert st.st_atime_ns == 1_000_000_000_000
assert st.st_mtime_ns == 2_000_000_000_000
```

